{{About|geological formation|the instrument used in Oceanography|Sediment trap|the device used on construction sites|Sediment trap (construction)}}
<!---permanent geology feature, not a temp. construction structure---{{Merge to|Sediment basin|date=September 2010}}--->

In [[geology]], a '''sediment trap''' is any [[Depression (geology)|topographic depression]] where [[sediments]] substantially accumulate over time. The size of a sediment trap can vary from a small [[lagoon]]<ref>{{cite journal
 | last = Ritter | first = John R.
 | title = Cyclic Sedimentation in Agua Hedionda Lagoon, Southern California
 | journal = Journal of the Waterways | volume = 98 | issue = 4 | date = November 1972 | pages = 597–602
 | publisher = Harbors and Coastal Engineering Division
 | url = http://cedb.asce.org/cgi/WWWdisplay.cgi?7200599
}}</ref> to a large basin such as the [[Persian Gulf]].

