{{italic title}} {{Infobox book | name = We Have Never Been Modern | image = We Have Never Been Modern.jpg| caption = | alt = | author = [[Bruno Latour]] | title_orig = Nous n'avons jamais été modernes: Essai d'anthropologie symétrique | orig_lang_code = fr | working_title = | translator = Catherine Porter | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = France, United States | language = English | series = | subjects = [[Science and technology studies]], [[philosophy of science]] | genre = | published = {{plainlist| * 1991 ([[La Découverte]]) (French) * 1993 ([[Harvard University Press]]) (English)}} | pages = 157 | awards = | isbn = 0-674-94838-6 | oclc = 27894925 | congress = Q175.5.L3513 1993 | preceded_by = [[Science in Action (book)|Science in Action]] | followed_by = [[Aramis, or the Love of Technology]] | wikisource = }}
'''''We Have Never Been Modern''''' is a 1991 book by [[Bruno Latour]], originally published in French as ''Nous n'avons jamais été modernes : Essai d'anthropologie symétrique'' (English translation: 1993).<ref>{{Cite book | publisher = Harvard University Press | isbn = 978-0-674-94839-6 | last = Latour | first = Bruno | title = We have never been modern | year = 1993 | page = iv | url = https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=TzQAPY8-S7UC&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=we+have+never+been+modern&ots=F0UBEZhkrx&sig=SuovAwURAodJncvg4EByCje9MbE#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref>
==Content== The book is an "anthropology of science" that explores the dualistic distinction [[modernity]] makes between [[nature]] and [[society]]. [[Pre-modern]] peoples, argues Latour, made no such division. Contemporary matters of public concern such as [[global warming]], the [[HIV/AIDS pandemic]] and emerging [[biotechnologies]] mix politics, science, popular and specialist discourse to such a degree that a tidy nature/culture dualism is no longer possible. This inconsistency has given rise to [[post-modern]] and [[Anarcho-primitivism|anti-modern]] movements<!--NOTE: the link to "Anarcho-primitivism" is only a rough and far from ideal fit to Latour's conception of "anti-modernism". Insert a better one if you can-->. Latour attempts to reconnect the social and natural worlds by arguing that the modernist distinction between nature and culture never existed. He claims we must rework our thinking to conceive of a "Parliament of Things" wherein [[natural phenomena]], [[social phenomena]] and the [[discourse]] about them are not seen as separate objects to be studied by [[experts|specialist]]s, but as [[wikt:hybrid|hybrids]] made and scrutinized by the public interaction of people, things and concepts.<ref>{{Cite book | publisher = Harvard University Press | isbn = 978-0-674-94839-6 | last = Latour | first = Bruno | title = We have never been modern | year = 1993 | pages = 142–145, back cover | url = https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=TzQAPY8-S7UC&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=we+have+never+been+modern&ots=F0UBEZhkrx&sig=SuovAwURAodJncvg4EByCje9MbE#v=onepage&q&f=false }} </ref><ref>{{Cite journal | issn = 1080-6601 | volume = 1 | issue = 3 | pages = 257–258 | last = Pickering | first = Andrew. | title = We Have Never Been Modern (review) | journal = Modernism/modernity | accessdate = 2010-08-10 | year = 1994 | url = http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/modernism-modernity/v001/1.3br_latour.html }}</ref>
